  Step 5: Implement Authentication-Related API Routes
Now, we will refactor  to add registration, login, logout, and current user state management functions. This is a relatively large update. (Final complete version)This file mainly made these changes: Added the  function: This function will read the  cookie in the request to identify the current user. In subsequent routes, we can directly get the logged-in user's information through Depends(get_current_user). Added routes related to user registration and login

: The GET request displays the registration form, and the POST request handles the form submission. It will check if the username already exists, then hash the password and store it in the database.: The GET request displays the login form. The POST request will verify the username and password. If successful, it will set a cookie named  in the response and set the user's username as the value. This is a simple session implementation.: Clears the  cookie and redirects back to the homepage.: The  route now depends on . If the user is not logged in, it will redirect to the login page. When posting, the  of the post will be automatically set to the ID of the currently logged-in user.: Routes such as  will now get the current user's information and pass it to the template so that the login status can be displayed on the page.


  Step 6: Update the Homepage Template to Display User Status
Finally, we need to modify  so that it can display different content based on the user's login status. (Updated)My FastAPI ForumWelcome to My Forum
